# local-llm-import-export — Project Overview

## What Is This?

local-llm-import-export is a browser-based tool that packages documents and a local language model into a single portable zip file. You can then import that zip and chat with the knowledge base completely offline — no internet required after the initial export.

## Two Apps

### Export App (port 5198)
- Drag and drop source documents (PDF, DOCX, TXT, MD)
- Write or paste custom system instructions for the chat assistant
- Choose a chat model (Gemma 2B recommended, Phi-3-mini for best quality, TinyLlama for speed)
- Click Start Export → pick a save location → the app streams the zip directly to disk
- The export fetches model weights from HuggingFace CDN once and packages everything

### Import App (port 5199)
- Drop the exported zip file onto the page
- The app extracts it in a background worker — never blocks the UI
- Model weights go into the browser's Cache API (WebLLM reads them as if cached from network)
- Knowledge base index goes into OPFS (Origin Private File System)
- Once loaded, chat works 100% offline with no…

[DOC 3 — troubleshooting.txt]
TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE — local-llm-import-export
================================================

EXPORT APP ISSUES
-----------------

Problem: File picker does not open / "Must be handling a user gesture"
Solution: showSaveFilePicker requires a direct user gesture (click). If the file
picker opens only after async work (parsing, embedding), the gesture context is
lost. The fix is to call showSaveFilePicker as the very first line of the export
handler before any awaits.

Problem: Export crashes with out-of-memory error near end of export
Solution: Never pass model shards through the main thread. The zip-worker must
fetch model shards directly from HuggingFace using fetch() inside the worker,
then pipe them through fflate ZipPassThrough. Main thread only handles small KB
entries (manifest, chunks, index).

Problem: Export hangs at "Parsing..." with no progress
Solution: The document-worker may have failed to parse a file. Check browser
console for PARSE_ERROR messages. PDF parsing uses pdfjs-dist — make sure the
PDF is not password-protected or corrupt. DOCX parsing uses mammoth.js.…

